, she reflected on the relevance of our past to understanding our present. Deeply informed by archival research and current scholarship, but written as a reflective and intimate memoir, What the Oceans Remember addresses current issues in migration, identity, belonging, and history through an interrogation of race, ethnicity, gender, archives and memory. More importantly, it addresses the relevance of our past to understanding our present. It shows the multiplicity of identities and origins that can shape the way we understand our histories and our own selves.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aBelonging (Social psychology). 0aHomexPsychological aspects. 0aIdentity (Psychology). 4aLife Writing. 4aSocial Science: Emigration & Immigration. 4aSocial Science: Multiculturalism. 4aSocial Science: Women’s studies. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Cultural, Ethnic & Regional / African American & Black.2bisacsh  a.  aAncestry.  aArchives.  aAutobiography and memoir.  aBelonging.  aCanadian identity.  aClassical music.  aColonialism.  aCreative history.  aCreative nonfiction.  aFamily history.  aFlute.  aGenealogy.  aGenerations.  aGlobal history.  aIdentity.  aIndenture.  aIndia.  aMemory.  aMixed-race identity.  aMulticulturalism.  aNewfoundland.  aPlace-based identity.  aSlavery.  aSpeculative biography.  aSuriname.  aTravel.  amicro-history.  athe Netherlands.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311127268908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2019z978311127498040uhttps://doi.org/10.51644/978177112424940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781771124249423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781771124249/original  a978-3-11-127268-9  ACUP Complete eBoo